---
/**
 * Roadmap — public-facing end-user variant of the Wakir Labs build
 * plan. No date anchors, no ADR ids, no internal milestone numbers;
 * the substance is what we are building, in what order, and what is
 * already running today.
 *
 * Sister pages:
 *
 *   - `/verifier/`     — read the output of a single verifier run
 *   - `/audit-trail/`  — timeline of artefacts the runtime has anchored
 *   - `/about/`        — what Wakir Labs is, and how we publish
 *
 * Substance source:
 *   `agents-workspaces/mira/outbox/2026-05-07-roadmap-enduser-skizze.md`
 *   (Variante 1, supervisory-board approved). Wording on this page is
 *   the approved substance, lightly smoothed for brand-voice
 *   consistency with the existing essay surface (about, audit-trail,
 *   verifier, why-we-are-wakir-labs).
 *
 * Brand discipline:
 *   - Brand-Guide §9: role-strings only, no clear-names, no persona
 *     count statement on the page. The roadmap names systems
 *     (audit trail, identity, capability tokens, container
 *     orchestrator, persona engine), not people.
 *   - ADR-0048-16 honesty pattern: every "what is next" item is
 *     described as a build item, not a finished result. The
 *     roadmap-page is a plan document, not a launch announcement.
 *   - No date anchors in the running text (supervisory-board
 *     directive 2026-05-07: end-user variant ships without
 *     calendar-bound milestones). Sequencing is described in terms
 *     of dependencies and order, not weeks or quarters.
 *   - No hype adjectives, no "trustless" badges, no marketing
 *     pills, no future-proof claims. We describe what we are
 *     building; the receipts elsewhere on the site decide whether
 *     it works.
 *
 * Cross-Review-Hooks:
 *   - Comms Zone-G (Júlia): stage-1 micro-text review pending. The
 *     wording below is the approved substance, but the running text
 *     has been smoothed; brand-voice review applies.
 *   - Supervisory-board pre-go-live review pending. Site-push
 *     remains dev-engineering hand; this page ships on a feature
 *     branch.
 */
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import WakirBrandAssetCard from "../components/WakirBrandAssetCard.astro";
import NewsletterCTA from "../components/NewsletterCTA.astro";

const title = "Roadmap";
const description =
  "What Wakir Labs runs today, what is next, and what comes after. End-user view of the build plan, in order, without date anchors.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="essay">
    <header class="essay__header">
      <p class="essay__meta">
        <span>Roadmap</span>
        <span>plan, not announcement</span>
      </p>
      <h1 class="essay__title">Roadmap</h1>
      <p class="essay__lead">
        What Wakir Labs runs today, what is next on the build, and what
        comes after. The roadmap is sequenced by dependencies, not by
        a calendar; the order below is the order we plan to ship in.
        This is a plan document, not a launch announcement.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="essay__body">
      <h2>What runs today</h2>

      <p>
        We operate a pipeline in which every agent action is signed,
        bound to a capability token, and anchored hourly to the
        Bitcoin blockchain. An external reviewer can use a
        command-line tool against a local archive to check whether a
        reported event is part of the confirmed audit trail. First
        live data points are embedded on this site &mdash; a
        multi-hour run with four independent Bitcoin confirmations
        is linked below.
      </p>

      <WakirBrandAssetCard
        variant="medium"
        crossReferenceHref="/audit-trail/"
        crossReferenceLabel="See the full audit-trail timeline"
      />

      <p>
        Two reading surfaces follow from this:
        <a href="/verifier/">how to read the output of a single
        verifier run</a> for the per-receipt verdict, and
        <a href="/audit-trail/">the audit-trail timeline</a> for the
        chronological list of artefacts the runtime has anchored.
      </p>

      <h2>What is next</h2>

      <p>
        Four build items, in dependency order. Each is in flight; none
        is finished. The roadmap-page updates when an item lands.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Verifier in the browser.</strong> The audit tool
          becomes accessible as a small web surface, without the
          command line. Input: an event id and a local archive.
          Output: the block heights that carry the event.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Identity system production-ready.</strong> Every
          agent gets a stable key and a signed persona definition
          with a deterministic hash. A persona engine handles spawn,
          recovery, and migration between runtime versions.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Capability tokens with external-library
          compatibility.</strong> Tokens carry caveats &mdash;
          <em>only inside a trusted-execution environment</em>,
          <em>only once</em>, <em>only after a given time</em> &mdash;
          and are checkable with a publicly-maintained library, not
          only with our own.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Container orchestrator.</strong> Agents run in
          containers whose start, migration, and stop are themselves
          part of the audit trail.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Cross-organisation verification</h2>

      <p>
        An organisation that runs the system anchors its audit
        substrate with a publicly-resolvable DNS record. A second
        organisation can &mdash; without a prior contract, without a
        central registry &mdash; verify the audit trail of the first.
        DNS and Bitcoin carry the trust anchors; no third service
        sits between them. We build the resolver for that inside the
        substrate. From the outside, only standard protocols are
        needed.
      </p>

      <h2>Tech spec</h2>

      <p>
        Once the five modules &mdash; audit trail, identity,
        capability tokens, container orchestrator, persona engine
        &mdash; are stable, a v1 whitepaper freezes the
        specification for external implementers. Before that, we
        publish a position paper that describes the modules without
        committing to spec text, as a substance anchor for early
        reviewers.
      </p>

      <h2>Onboarding for external operator organisations</h2>

      <p>Three maturity stages, in order:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Stage 1.</strong> A first external organisation
          sets up the pipeline self-hosted, with our hands-on
          guidance.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stage 2.</strong> Several independent organisations
          run their own instances in parallel, each with its own
          DNS-anchored federation document. Cross-organisation
          verification runs as routine.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stage 3.</strong> Onboarding is documented and
          works without our direct involvement. Federation is an
          open network, not a central system.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Self-migration</h2>

      <p>
        We migrate our own organisation onto the substrate we build,
        in parallel. Once that runs stably, the old stack is
        switched off. We eat what we cook, before anyone else does.
      </p>

      <h2>Phase 2 and beyond</h2>

      <p>
        Federation is not the end. Confidential execution, key
        rotation, recovery paths for lost persona keys, and tooling
        for external auditors are the next steps. The order is set
        by the actual demand of the first operator organisations,
        not by our internal plan.
      </p>

      <h2>How this page works</h2>

      <p>
        The roadmap is sequenced by dependencies. We do not put
        dates on it &mdash; calendar-bound milestones drift, and a
        published drift turns into a credibility problem we do not
        need. When a build item lands, this page updates and the
        artefact shows up on
        <a href="/audit-trail/">the audit-trail timeline</a>. The
        timeline is the receipt; this page is the plan.
      </p>

      <p class="essay__signoff">&mdash; Wakir Labs Editorial</p>
    </div>

    <NewsletterCTA variant="inline" />
  </article>
</Base>
